node.text:
Japan is the world's 11th-most-populous country and has its third-largest economy. ⁠
⁠
It is peaceful, stable and democratic. ⁠
⁠
Despite that the Land of the Rising Sun has little visibility on the global scene, however. ⁠
⁠
The Japanese do not go around tooting their own horn; when foreigners mention the island nation it is usually to rave about a great holiday or a curious pastime. ⁠
⁠
That will change in 2020 as Tokyo prepares to host the summer Olympics. ⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read how the nation's leaders want to use that to Japan's advantage.⁠
⁠
Credit: Issei Kato/Reuters

In 1876 Sigmund Freud dissected 400 eels looking for testicles. He was flummoxed—there were none. ⁠
⁠
To this day, the eel's mating habits remain a scientific mystery.⁠
⁠
The fact that nobody knows exactly how eels reproduce is something that matters for the future of the species.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read about the mysterious life and times of these creatures, and why their numbers are dwindling in the wild.

Yeoville in Johannesberg is probably Africa's greatest melting pot.⁠
⁠
Probably nowhere else on the continent do so many communities live in such proximity—it has been a temporary home to Nelson Mandela and Mahatma Gandhi.⁠
⁠
But while xenophobia may not be a problem in the neighbourhood, crime is. ⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio read how the area has changed drastically, but still retains a rare vibrancy.⁠
⁠
Credit: James Oatway/Panos

Two of the world’s great cultures are butting heads. ⁠
⁠
In one corner is the Anglosphere—America, Britain, Canada, Australia and New Zealand—a group of rich, English-speaking countries with open societies and a streak of gleeful irreverence. ⁠
⁠
In the other is the Sinosphere, a sterner place where deference to the leader-for-life is not merely expected but required. ⁠
⁠
The Sinosphere consists mostly of the People’s Republic of China, but also includes those under its sway.⁠
⁠
They are increasingly suspicious of one another, but click the link in our bio to read why they need to get on better in 2020.⁠
⁠
Illustration: Nick Lowndes

Elephant dung is fuelling South Africa's gin boom.⁠
⁠
Distillers are infusing their products with poo to capture "the textures and flavours of the African bush" and sell it for 659 rand ($46) a bottle.⁠
⁠
Sales are estimated to have jumped by 54% in a year for the industry as a whole.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to find out about the three factors that explain this boom.

The conditions for America to do foreign-policy deals in 2020 could hardly seem worse.⁠
⁠
The effort to impeach President Donald Trump has made the country's diplomacy toxic, with suspicion and potential leaks apt to poison any big initiative. ⁠
⁠
Relations with America's emerging challenger, China, have settled into deep distrust. ⁠
⁠
And those with its traditional rival, Russia, look flimsier, in terms of the strategic dialogue between officials that minimises misunderstanding, than at any time since the height of the cold war. ⁠
⁠
Yet in the vital area of nuclear arms-control there is an urgency to get back to business.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to learn why these two nations—which own 90% of the world's nuclear weapons—have an opportunity to do so in 2020⁠.⁠
⁠
Credit: Sergei Bobylev/TASS via Getty Images

When someone suggests Italian food for dinner, your first thought might be a rich tomato sauce splattered over pasta. ⁠
⁠
But the key ingredients of Italian cuisine are relatively new—and there is little record of long pasta or the tomato before the Middle Ages. ⁠
⁠
Food archaeologists have discovered that 2,000 years ago Italians had a very different diet. ⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read what Italian cuisine tasted like in the ages before its most popular ingredients arrived, in an article from @1843mag.⁠
⁠
Credit: Daniel McAlister

A recession is not inevitable in 2020. ⁠
⁠
In many countries, especially America, healthy labour markets and confident consumers are defences against one.⁠
⁠
Yet cracks are beginning to show, and the world economy is teetering on the brink of an unfamiliar type of downturn.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read how a scary scenario could unfold next year.

Where do you fancy as a place to retire? If it's sun-drenched #Monaco then you're in good company.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read the full top 40 list of nations with more older people than any other, from The Economist's World in Figures website.

The California of glossy dreams is the California of palm trees. ⁠
⁠
But the real California is the California of the eucalyptus.⁠
⁠
Nobody knows quite when eucalyptus trees first reached the state. But when they arrived, they thrived.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to find out what happens when a dream grows and then falters on foreign soil.⁠
⁠
Credit: Alamy

In the late 1950s the British government was trying to push factories and workers out of London. ⁠
⁠
#Thetford offered to take so many that its population would triple. ⁠
⁠
Today this small town in eastern England resembles a 50-year-old East End, transported to the rural landscape of East Anglia. ⁠
⁠
This makes it an excellent place to visit if you want to understand the white, working-class, Brexit-supporting Englishman. ⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read what happens when you take thousands of working-class Londoners and drop them in the middle of nowhere.

Between 2009 and 2018 the share of teenagers who read newspapers declined from around 60% to close to 20%, according to the Programme for International Student Assessment. ⁠
⁠
Young Indians are half as likely to visit timesofindia.com, India's biggest English-language news site, as older ones; they are also far more interested in videos and Bollywood news. ⁠
⁠
In Britain, younger teens are far less familiar with the BBC's brand than they are with those of YouTube or Netflix. ⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to learn how young people are rewriting the rules of the news—and why that will affect both the industry and society.⁠
⁠
Illustration: @jackrichardson_illustration

The worst a chocolate binge can do for a mischievous child is a dizzying sugar high. ⁠
⁠
For dogs, however, the theobromine found in cocoa beans can cause vomiting, diarrhoea and seizures. ⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read about a study of British vet clinics that found a large spike in canine chocolate intoxication in the weeks around Easter and Christmas.⁠
⁠
(It's an article we published last Easter, but it also applies at this time of year.)

Two planes from the same airline crashed in the same spot in the Alps, 16 years apart. ⁠
⁠
Now the melting ice is revealing their secrets and making them impossible to ignore. ⁠
⁠
@1843mag travelled to Chamonix, in France, to meet the investigator who believes the truth behind the disasters has been buried.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read how a glacier is releasing secrets that have stayed frozen for six decades.⁠
⁠
Credit: Nicolas Blandin

The Economist's books of the year include a timely polemic against philanthrocapitalism, a masterful exploration of the motives of terrorists, and an ingeniously structured double mystery.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read the list in full.⁠
⁠
Illustration: @nathalielees

Our Christmas quiz is here—and there are prizes.⁠
⁠
This year's competition is based on ten famous economists.⁠
⁠
Four questions are loosely linked to each one, and a fifth requires the connection between the four.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to take part. Good luck!⁠
⁠
Illustration: @selmanhosgor⁠
China’s love affair with the piano has flourished in the past century, and four-fifths of the world’s pianos are now produced there. How did China make the Western instrument its own?

Digital printing almost wiped out the world's letterpresses 40 years ago, but the art refuses to die.⁠
⁠
In a few corners of the world, particularly in Japan, old fonts and machines show no signs of going away.⁠
⁠
And the resurgence of hot-metal type printing has been likened to the revival of vinyl records.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read how the world's old printing presses are being brought back to life.⁠
⁠
Credit: The Economist/Ben Shmulevitch

Of all the actors in the Nativity story, the three wise men are by far the most fun.⁠
⁠
But what do these magical, royal wanderers through the desert really signify?⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read about their true meaning, in an archive article from our 2014 Christmas issue.⁠
⁠
Credit: Bridgeman

The key to the future is open collaboration, according to Ren Zhengfei, the CEO and founder of Huawei.⁠
⁠
Staff at the technology company believe that humanity will enter an intelligent world within the next 20 to 30 years, he says. ⁠
⁠
"Society is on the verge of another explosion of new theories and technologies," he writes for The World in 2020, our annual look at the year ahead.⁠
⁠
Click the link in the bio to read why he feels there is a lot of potential, but also much uncertainty—and where he envisages significant breakthroughs in the coming decades.⁠
⁠
Credit: Bloomberg

Humans eat so many chickens that the birds now count for 23bn of the 30bn land animals living on farms⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to find out how chicken became the rich world's most popular meat.⁠
⁠
This was one of our most-read articles of 2019.

Put your hand on the back of your head, where the skull curves down to the neck. ⁠
⁠
Your cerebellum is an inch or two beneath your palm, a dense knot of brain tissue which sits slightly apart from the rest. ⁠
⁠
In just 10% of the brain's volume, the cerebellum contains half of all its cells. ⁠
⁠
You would think that would mean it was vital—but one boy was born without it.⁠
⁠
Although his life has its challenges, it is in most ways pretty close to normal—because what his absent cerebellum cannot do, the rest of his brain and the rest of his family can.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to find out how, in an archive article from our 2018 Christmas issue.⁠
⁠
Credit: Logan Mock-Bunting/Zuma/eyevine

Because China is so populous and is developing so quickly, it is responsible for a remarkable share of global change. ⁠
⁠
In the decade since the start of the financial crisis in 2008, for example, China accounted for 45% of the gain in world GDP. ⁠
⁠
In 1990 some 750m Chinese people lived in extreme poverty; today fewer than 10m do. ⁠
⁠
This represents two-thirds of the world's decline in poverty during that time. ⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to read why, when scholars of international relations predicted that the 2000s would be a "Chinese century", they were not being premature.

Earlier this month a missile streaked into the sky above Vandenberg air force base north of Los Angeles. ⁠
⁠
It looped up into the blackness of space and then hurtled down into the Pacific—crucially, over 500km away. ⁠
⁠
That makes it America's first test of a ballistic missile that would have been forbidden under the 1987 Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty.⁠
⁠
This had banned both conventional and nuclear land-based missiles (but not air or sea-launched ones) with ranges of 500km to 5,500km.⁠
⁠
Click the link in our bio to find out why America has big plans for new mid-range ballistic missiles⁠.⁠
⁠
Credit: Staff Sgt. J.T. Armstrong/US Air Force

By the age of three, children from professional families will have 30m more words spoken to them than children from poorer backgrounds. Part of the problem could be that modern families are increasing inequality.
